-- stdlib/passes/validate.ev — the SOLE external-only check.
--
-- The load-time rule that rejects non-`external` schemas which
-- directly construct FFI effects (`FFICall` / `FFIOpen` /
-- `FFILookup` / `LibCall`). Demos and ordinary library code reach C
-- through `external claim` wrappers in `packages/` and
-- `stdlib/posix.ev`; the runtime refuses to compile a non-`external`
-- claim that does so itself.
--
-- As of the validate cutover (session VV) this pass IS the
-- implementation — the canonical Rust `enforce_external_only` is
-- deleted. The runtime's load path (runtime/src/runtime/load.rs)
-- builds one validator per runtime and routes every schema through
-- it via `EvidentValidate` in runtime/src/portable/validate.rs.
--
-- This pass owns the decision logic — what counts as a banned call
-- name. The Rust shim owns the walk: it iterates a schema's body
-- items, recurses into each Constraint's Expr tree, and queries
-- `ValidateExpr` with the call name at every Call node. Per-Call
-- classification lives in Evident; structural recursion stays in
-- Rust because the language can't recurse over nested Expr trees
-- yet (see `docs/self-hosting.md`).
--
-- ── Why `nm ∈ String` and not `e ∈ Expr` ──────────────────────
-- The natural shape — match the whole Expr, destructure ECall, pin
-- and compare its name field — runs into a runtime gap: a String
-- payload extracted from a given-pinned enum value doesn't preserve
-- byte equality with a source-literal string. `match e { ECall(nm,
-- _) ⇒ (nm = "FFICall" ? ...) }` evaluates the comparison to false
-- on both JIT and slow paths even when the bytes match. Pinning
-- `nm` directly side-steps the gap: the runtime threads the
-- given-bound String to the comparison without going through the
-- enum-extractor. The pattern is still genuinely self-hosted (the
-- "banned ⇔ name ∈ {...}" decision lives here), and the shim's
-- Rust walker decides WHEN to ask. See
-- `examples/COUNTEREXAMPLES.md` for the gap entry.
--
-- ── No AST import ──────────────────────────────────────────────
-- `ValidateExpr` is a pure `String → String` claim and references no
-- AST type, so this file does NOT `import "stdlib/ast.ev"`. That
-- keeps the validator a single 1-claim load with no enum
-- registration — cheap enough to build on every runtime that loads a
-- file. (When the given-pinned-enum gap above is closed and the pass
-- can take `e ∈ Expr`, the import comes back with it.)

-- Classify a call name. Returns `nm` itself when it's one of the
-- four banned FFI-construction primitives; empty string otherwise.
-- The shim treats a non-empty return as a found-violation signal
-- and uses the returned name in the diagnostic.
claim ValidateExpr
    nm ∈ String
    out ∈ String
    out = ((nm = "FFICall" ∨ nm = "FFIOpen" ∨ nm = "FFILookup" ∨ nm = "LibCall") ? nm : "")
